Kick off with JAR file
-	Yes, for this migration I would start by running it as a JAR task in Databricks.
-	
-	Reason: your Airflow DAG already runs each task as a compiled Scala main class from the AudAuto assembly jar:
-	
-	eldorado-audauto-assembly.jar
-	For Task 1, the main class is:
-	
-	model.fpcookiescoring.GenerateCampaignScores
-	So the closest Databricks baseline is:
-	
-	Databricks Job Task Type: JAR
-	Main class: model.fpcookiescoring.GenerateCampaignScores
-	Jar: eldorado-audauto-assembly.jar
-	That keeps the migration clean because you are only changing the compute platform first:
-	
-	Airflow + EMR + same jar
-	        to
-	Databricks workflow + Databricks cluster + same jar
-	You are not changing business logic yet.
-	
-	I would avoid starting with notebooks unless your goal is to refactor. Notebooks are useful later for debugging, sampling, and validation, but the first baseline should be JAR-based so you can compare EMR vs Databricks outputs fairly.
-	
-	Recommended sequence:
-	
-	1. Run existing JAR on Databricks.
-	2. Pass the same config values from the DAG.
-	3. Write outputs to sandbox paths first.
-	4. Compare output schemas/counts/samples with EMR.
-	5. Only then decide whether to refactor into notebooks or keep as JAR jobs.
-	For Task 1 specifically:
-	
-	JAR task
-	Main class: model.fpcookiescoring.GenerateCampaignScores
-	Configs:
-	  date=YYYY-MM-DD
-	  useNewSources=true
-	  trainingWindowDays=14
-	  labelWindowDays=1
-	  testWindowDays=2
-	  openlineage.enable=false
-	  generateDebugTables=false
-	So short answer: yes, start with JAR files. That is the lowest-risk migration path.
EMR Cluster configuration
Yes. This DAG uses a different EMR cluster per task, and each task has different Spark/job config.
All four clusters are created with the same helper:
emr_cluster_factory.py (line 136)
python
create_emr_cluster_r7g(...)
That means all four are EMR Spark 3.5 r7g clusters:
text
EMR release: AWS_EMR_SPARK_3_5 Master: r7g.4xlarge, 300 GB EBS Core fleet choices: r7g.8xlarge r7g.16xlarge Logs: s3://thetradedesk-mlplatform-us-east-1/logs/emr/audauto Extra app: Hadoop Prometheus monitoring: enabled
Shared EMR app config:
utils.py (line 149)
text
emrfs-site: fs.s3.maxConnections = 1000 fs.s3.maxRetries = 60 fs.s3.sleepTimeSeconds = 15 spark-hive-site: hive.metastore.client.factory.class = com.amazonaws.glue.catalog.metastore.AWSGlueDataCatalogHiveClientFactory
Shared per-job configs:
perf-automation-fpcs.py (line 20)
text
spark.sql.objectHashAggregate.sortBased.fallbackThreshold = 4096 date = logical_date + 1 day spark.executor.extraJavaOptions = -server -XX:+UseParallelGC jar = s3://ttd-build-artefacts/eldorado/release-spark-3/main-spark-3/latest/eldorado-audauto-assembly.jar
